moons pull on earth

F = Gmm/r²
F = [6.67e-11][7.3477e22][5.9742e24] / [3.844e8]²
F = 1.98e20 N

The moon exerts about 198 exanewtons of force on the Earth, and vice versa (by Newton's third law). 

exanewton

    The newton (symbol: N) is the International System of Units (SI) derived unit of force. It is named after Isaac Newton in recognition of his work on classical mechanics, specifically Newton's second law of motion.
    
An exanewton (EN) is a SI-multiple (see prefix Exa) of the force unit newton and equal to 1,000,000,000,000,000,000 newtons

newton

the SI unit of force. It is equal to the force that would give a mass of one kilogram an acceleration of one meter per second per second, and is equivalent to 100,000 dynes.
